
[1]oppose

   OPPO'SE, v.t. s as z. [L. oppono, opposui. The change of n into s is
   unusual. Two different verbs may be used, as in L. fero, tuli. See
   Pose.]

   1. To set; against; to put in opposition, with a view to counterbalance
   or countervail, and thus to hinder defeat, destroy or prevent effect;
   as, to oppose one argument to another.

   I may without presumption oppose my single opinion to his.

   2. To act against; to resist, either by physical means, by arguments or
   other means. The army opposed the progress of the enemy, but without
   success. Several members of the house strenuously opposed the bill, but
   it passed.

   3. To check; to resist effectually. The army was not able to oppose the
   progress of the enemy.

   4. To place in front; to set opposite.

   5. To act against, as a competitor.
